-- 
Ringgit Slides on Signs Global Growth Easing, Europe Debt Risks

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-06-13T09:11:27Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-13/ringgit-slides-on-signs-global-growth-easing-europe-debt-risks.html
Malaysia’s ringgit fell the most in
three weeks as indications the global economic recovery is
losing steam curbed demand for riskier assets, making it harder
for emerging markets to attract funds.  The currency retreated in all but one of the last six weeks
as a worsening debt crisis in  Europe  bolstered demand for
dollars. Malaysia reported last week that industrial production
shrank in April for the first time since November 2009, while
 Japan  announced today its first monthly drop in machinery orders
of 2011. Government bonds fell before an auction.  “Manufacturing data are indicating a slowdown and the
Europe situation will likely take months to resolve,” said
Calbert Loh, head of treasury at Bangkok Bank Bhd. in  Kuala
Lumpur . “This could bring back double-dip concerns and limit
the ringgit appreciation trend.”  The ringgit dropped 0.7 percent to 3.0425 per dollar as of
5 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by Bloomberg,
the biggest drop since May 23. The currency has depreciated 1.3
percent in the past month, the biggest loser among  Asia ’s 10
most-traded currencies.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index of stocks fell for a fourth day,
losing 0.6 percent. Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker said on June 11 that a bailout for  Greece  must include
“voluntary” investor participation and meet the approval of
central bankers.  ‘Perfect Storm’  A “perfect storm” of fiscal woe in the U.S., a slowdown
in  China , European debt restructuring and stagnation in Japan
may converge on the global economy, New York University
professor Nouriel Roubini said on June 11 in Singapore.  Malaysia’s benchmark 10-year bonds declined as the
government prepares to sell more of the securities tomorrow.  The yield on the 4.16 percent note due July 2021 rose 1
basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 3.95 percent,
according to Bursa Malaysia. The price dropped 0.15, or 1.5
ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face amount, to 101.7.  The treasury will auction 4 billion ringgit ($1.3 billion)
of the 2021 notes in the first of two offerings scheduled this
month. The government has raised 43.5 billion ringgit from bond
sales this year through May, versus 24.5 billion ringgit in the
same period last year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
